WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
This is Jacob's Research Journal. Today's deep dive: What "fifty-five

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
percent replicate" actually means. The headline number from the biggest

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
replication study social science has ever run sounds almost reassuring.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Fifty-five percent of findings held up. Slightly better than a

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
coin flip. Half the building is still standing. But "fifty-five

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
percent replicate" is, it turns out, the optimistic interpretation. If

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
you look at what happened to the studies that did

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
replicate — not just whether they were statistically significant, but

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
how big the effects were — the picture looks considerably

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
worse. The median effect size in original papers was a

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Pearson's r of zero-point-two-five. In the replications, it was zero-point-one-zero.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
That's an eighty-two-point-four percent reduction in shared variance. The researchers

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
ran these replications with median statistical power of ninety-nine-point-six percent,

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
meaning they were essentially guaranteed to detect the original effect

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
if it existed at the original size. What they found

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
instead was a ghost of it. That number deserves more

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
attention than it's getting. The study. In April twenty-twenty-six, Nature

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
published a suite of companion papers reporting the results of

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
a years-long, multi-institution effort to replicate and assess reproducibility across

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
the social and behavioral sciences. The primary replication paper, led

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
by researchers affiliated with dozens of universities, attempted to replicate

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
two hundred and seventy-four specific claims from one hundred and

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
sixty-four papers published between two-thousand-nine and two-thousand-eighteen, drawn from fifty-four

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
journals spanning psychology, economics, sociology, education, and political science. The

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
replications were pre-registered, used original materials wherever available, and were

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
internally peer-reviewed before the results were known. This wasn't a

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
sloppy gotcha exercise — it was as rigorous as large-scale

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
replication gets. The fifty-five-point-one percent figure — that's one hundred

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
and fifty-one of two hundred and seventy-four claims, with a

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
ninety-five percent confidence interval from forty-nine-point-two to sixty-point-nine percent —

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
is the rate at which replications produced a statistically significant

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
result in the same direction as the original. That's one

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
reasonable definition of "replication." But it's the most generous one.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
By a per-paper measure, accounting for papers with multiple claims,

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
the rate drops to forty-nine-point-three percent. And when you look

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
at effect sizes — how strong the effect is, not

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
just whether it exists — the picture changes completely. Even

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
papers that "replicated" did so at dramatically lower magnitudes. An

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
effect that was supposed to explain six percent of variance

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
in the original study explains one percent in the replication.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Statistically significant, but not the same finding. This matters because

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
most of what social-science findings get used for — policy

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
recommendations, media coverage, classroom instruction, clinical practice guidelines — depends

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
on magnitude, not just direction. Knowing that some intervention has

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
an effect on some outcome is almost useless. Knowing how

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
big the effect is, whether it's big enough to matter

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
in the real world, whether it replicates at practical scale

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
— that's what makes a finding actionable. And on that

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
standard, the replication picture is considerably darker than fifty-five percent.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
The citation paradox. The twenty-twenty-six Nature findings raise a question

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
that researchers had already started to answer before this study

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
was published: what actually happens after a finding fails to

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
replicate? In twenty-twenty-one, researchers Marta Serra-Garcia and Uri Gneezy published

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
a paper in Science Advances with an unsettling finding about

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
citation patterns. They looked at papers that had undergone replication

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
attempts and compared how often papers that replicated got cited

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
versus papers that didn't. The result: nonreplicable publications were cited

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
roughly sixteen times more per year than replicable ones. This

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
difference didn't change after the replication failures were published. More

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
striking: only twelve percent of citations to papers after a

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
failed replication made any reference to the failure. Think about

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
what that means structurally. The replication system is designed to

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
correct the scientific record. When a finding fails to replicate,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
the theory is that scientists update their beliefs, stop building

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
on that finding, and eventually it fades from the literature.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
The Serra-Garcia and Gneezy data shows that's not what happens.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
The record-correction mechanism is almost inert. Failed findings keep accumulating

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
citations, keep getting taught, keep influencing the research questions other

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
scientists ask. The correction is quietly ignored. Why? The incentives

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
are backwards. A surprising, counterintuitive finding that generates massive citations

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
— even if it later fails to replicate — makes

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
a career. The replication paper that kills it generates a

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
fraction of the attention. The journal that publishes the original

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
study benefits from the prestige; the journal that publishes the

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
correction benefits from very little. There's no formal mechanism to

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
demote a high-cited paper because it failed to replicate; it

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
still shows up at the top of Google Scholar, still

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
gets included in meta-analyses, still makes its way into the

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
textbooks. Discipline variation. The twenty-twenty-six Nature papers also show meaningful

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
variation across disciplines, which is analytically interesting because it suggests

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
the problem isn't uniformly distributed — and therefore might have

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
identifiable causes. Education achieved the highest replication rate at approximately

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
sixty-three percent; economics fell to the bottom at roughly forty-three

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
percent, according to coverage of the study. The specific discipline

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
rankings carry uncertainty given the small samples involved; the Nature

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
authors note that some discipline estimates have, quote, high uncertainty.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
One interpretation: economics has a higher rate of field experiments

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
and natural experiments that are inherently hard to replicate exactly,

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
because the circumstances change. Another interpretation: economics has stronger norms

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
around sharp causal identification than, say, social psychology — which

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
means the claims that make it into high-prestige journals are

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
more often exactly the kind of surprising, counterintuitive treatment effects

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
that are vulnerable to p-hacking and publication bias. The discipline

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
with the most rigorous-seeming methods may have the worst replication

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
problem precisely because the methods provide good cover for over-claiming.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
There's a companion paper in the same Nature issue on

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
economics and political science specifically, which found eighty-five percent of

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
published claims were computationally reproducible — meaning you can rerun

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
the code and get the same numbers — but only

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
seventy-two percent were statistically robust to reasonable variations in specification.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
Reproducibility and replicability are different standards. You can reproduce the

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
exact numbers from a published dataset while the underlying claim

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
still doesn't hold up in a new sample. The eighty-five

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
percent figure is often cited as reassuring; it's mostly measuring

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
whether the code runs, not whether the finding is real.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
Why reform isn't working. The obvious policy response to a

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
replication crisis is open science reform: pre-registration — committing publicly

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
to your hypothesis and analysis plan before running the experiment

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
— data sharing, and registered reports, where journals agree to

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
publish a study before seeing the results. These are good

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
ideas in principle, and they've been spreading through psychology and

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
economics for the better part of a decade. So how's

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
that working? The evidence is mixed, and some of it

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
is actively discouraging. A twenty-twenty-five analysis of articles that earned

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
pre-registration badges at Psychological Science found that eighty-nine percent included

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
undisclosed changes to the original pre-registration plan — modifications to

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
the hypothesis, the variables, the exclusion criteria, or the analytic

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
approach. The badge, meant to signal methodological rigor, was in

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
most cases masking researcher degrees of freedom just as it

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
was being claimed to eliminate them. The reform was being

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
gamed before it had fully arrived. Pre-registration doesn't fail because

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
scientists are dishonest. It fails because there's no credible enforcement

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
mechanism and the underlying incentives — the career reward for

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
a significant finding — haven't changed. If getting a significant

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
result is what gets you tenure and what gets you

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
published in the journals that confer prestige, and if pre-registration

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
only somewhat raises the cost of adjusting the analysis, many

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
researchers will adjust the analysis. The structural problem isn't transparency.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
It's that the currency of science is novel positive results,

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
and no amount of transparency reform changes what the market

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.000
is paying for. Registered reports — where journals agree in

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
advance to publish the results regardless of outcome — do

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
substantially better. A twenty-twenty-one analysis found that only forty-four percent

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.000
of registered report studies confirmed their primary hypothesis, compared to

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
ninety-six percent of conventional psychology publications. That fifty-two-point gap is

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
itself a measure of how much publication bias dominates the

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
conventional literature. What would actually help. A few things appear

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
promising. Results-blind peer review, where reviewers see the methods and

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
data but not the findings before deciding whether to accept

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
the paper, is another intervention with theoretical appeal and limited

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
empirical testing. Citation correction mechanisms — tools that automatically flag

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
high-cited papers with known replication failures in Google Scholar and

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
institutional databases — would help if they existed at scale.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
The harder problem is that science's incentive structure is set

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
by universities, not journals. Universities make hiring and tenure decisions

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
based on citation counts and journal prestige, both of which

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
currently reward the wrong things. Until those signals change —

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
until a lab that publishes ten rigorous small-effect replications is

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
as valuable on the market as one that publishes one

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
splashy overclocked positive result — the structural incentive to over-claim

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
remains. The number they chose to lead with. The fifty-five

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
percent headline is not a crisis number by accident. It's

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
the right number to announce. It sounds like the glass

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
is half full. It doesn't sound like the crisis is

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
ongoing, like the incentive structure is working against the correction

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
mechanism, like the effect sizes that did replicate came in

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
at about eighteen percent of their original explanatory power. It

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
sounds like a problem that science is working through. The

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
actual picture from the April twenty-twenty-six Nature study is that

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
the underlying incentive structure is largely unchanged. The most visible

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
sign: post-failure citation behavior shows the record-correction mechanism reaching only

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
twelve percent of subsequent scholarship on failed findings. The fields

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
most associated with rigorous causal identification may have the lowest

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
replication rates. And the reforms we've implemented so far are

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
being absorbed by the same incentive structure they were supposed

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.000
to fix. That's not a reason to distrust social science

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
wholesale — the fifty-five percent that replicated is real, and

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.000
the broader literature on effect sizes and statistical power has

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
genuinely changed how researchers design studies. But it is a

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.000
reason to read the next "surprising new study shows X"

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
headline with a different frame: not "this finding probably holds

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:28.000
up" but "this finding is surprising enough to have gotten

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
into a top journal, which means it was probably selected

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
for being surprising, which means it faces long odds." That's

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
the "What fifty-five percent replicate actually means" deep dive. Full

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
post and sources at jacobbrooke-ninety-five dot github dot i-o slash

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:45.600
jacobs-research-journal. Thanks for listening.
